@{
    ViewData["Title"] = "Home Page";
}

    <div class="container mt-5">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-10">
                <div class="card">
                    <div class="card-header text-center">
                        <h2>Employee Management System</h2>
                    </div>
                    <div class="card-body">
                        <h3>Project Overview</h3>
                        <p class="mb-4">This project is a simple <strong>Employee Management System</strong> built using ASP.NET MVC. The application allows users to perform basic CRUD (Create, Read, Update, Delete) operations on employee records. It showcases the core concepts of the MVC (Model-View-Controller) architectural pattern and demonstrates how to integrate a database using Entity Framework for data persistence.</p>

                        <h3>Technologies</h3>
                        <p class="mb-4"><span class="badge badge-primary">ASP.NET MVC</span> <span class="badge badge-success">C#</span> <span class="badge badge-info">Entity Framework</span> <span class="badge badge-warning">SQL Server</span></p>

                        <h3>Features</h3>
                        <ul class="list-group mb-4">
                            <li class="list-group-item">
                                <i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i> <strong>Employee List View:</strong> Displays a list of all employees with options to add, edit, or delete records.
                            </li>
                            <li class="list-group-item">
                                <i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i> <strong>Employee Details:</strong> Shows detailed information about a specific employee.
                            </li>
                            <li class="list-group-item">
                                <i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i> <strong>Add Employee:</strong> A form that allows users to add a new employee to the database.
                            </li>
                            <li class="list-group-item">
                                <i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i> <strong>Edit Employee:</strong> Enables users to update existing employee information.
                            </li>
                            <li class="list-group-item">
                                <i class="fas fa-check-circle"></i> <strong>Delete Employee:</strong> Provides the functionality to remove an employee from the system.
                            </li>
                        </ul>

                        <h3>Learning Objectives</h3>
                        <ul class="list-group mb-4">
                            <li class="list-group-item">
                                <i class="fas fa-lightbulb"></i> <strong>MVC Architecture:</strong> Understanding how to separate concerns using models, views, and controllers.
                            </li>
                            <li class="list-group-item">
                                <i class="fas fa-lightbulb"></i> <strong>Entity Framework:</strong> Learning to interact with a database using Code First and Database First approaches.
                            </li>
                            <li class="list-group-item">
                                <i class="fas fa-lightbulb"></i> <strong>Routing:</strong> Implementing routing to map URLs to the correct controller actions.
                            </li>
                            <li class="list-group-item">
                                <i class="fas fa-lightbulb"></i> <strong>Form Validation:</strong> Adding server-side and client-side validation to ensure data integrity.
                            </li>
                        </ul>

                        <h3>Challenges & Solutions</h3>
                        <p>During the development of this project, I encountered challenges such as configuring Entity Framework, managing database migrations, and implementing input validation. By researching best practices and experimenting with different approaches, I successfully overcame these obstacles and gained a deeper understanding of how to build robust web applications in C#.</p>
